    <div class="articleBoxContent">
    <div class="articleHeader">
      <h1><a href="/reviews/Mobile/Dell-Venue-8-7000-Review-Intel-and-Android-Perfected">The Dell Venue 8 7000 Review - Intel and Android Perfected</a></h1>
    </div>
            <div class="articleicon"><img src="http://www.pcper.com/files/imagecache/article_icon/review/2015-02-16/IMG_1719.jpg" alt="" title=""  class="imagecache imagecache-article_icon" width="152" height="102" /></div>
        <div class="authorBox">
      <div class="authorName">Author: <a href="/users/Ryan-Shrout" rel="author">Ryan Shrout</a></div>
      <div class="articleDate">Date: <span class="date">February 18, 2015</span></div>
      <div class="subject">Subject: <a href="/subject/mobile">Mobile</a></div>
              <div class="manufacturer">Manufacturer: <a href="http://www.dell.com/">Dell</a></div>
             <div class="subject">Tagged: <a href="/category/tags/video">video</a>, <a href="/category/tags/z3580">z3580</a>, <a href="/category/tags/venue-8-7000">venue 8 7000</a>, <a href="/category/tags/venue">venue</a>, <a href="/category/tags/tablet">tablet</a>, <a href="/category/tags/silvermont">silvermont</a>, <a href="/category/tags/moorefield">moorefield</a>, <a href="/category/tags/intel">Intel</a>, <a href="/category/tags/dell">dell</a>, <a href="/category/tags/atom-z3580">atom z3580</a>, <a href="/category/tags/android">Android</a></div>
    </div>
    <div class = "review-content">
    <h4>Specifications</h4>
          <p>Flagship. Premium. Best in class. These are the terms that Dell and Intel muttered to me during a conference call to discuss the new Dell Venue 8 7000 tablet. It&rsquo;s a bullish claim and one that would likely have been received with a sideways eye roll or a shrug had I not been able to get a short amount of hands on time with the device at CES in January. The idea that Dell would develop an Android tablet that bests what more established brands like Nexus and Samsung have created, AND that that same tablet would be powered by an Intel processor rather than a Qualcomm, NVIDIA or Samsung chip would have seemed laughable last year. But after a solid three weeks with the Venue 8 7000 I am prepared to make the statement: this is my favorite tablet. Not my favorite Intel tablet, not my favorite Android tablet: just plain favorite.</p>
<p class="rtecenter"><iframe allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/GQHGkjc0fWo" width="560"></iframe></p>
<p>The Venue 8 7000 combines style, design, technology and visuals that are simply unmatched by anything else in the Android word and rivals anything that Apple has created to date. There are a couple of warts that center around the camera and gaming performance that won&rsquo;t drop your jaw, but for the majority of use cases the user experience is as exceptional as the looks.</p>
<p><div class = "center-article-image"><a href="/reviews/Mobile/Dell-Venue-8-7000-Review-Intel-and-Android-Perfected" class="inline-image-link" title="View: IMG_1737.jpg"><img src="/files/imagecache/article_min_width/review/2015-02-16/IMG_1737.jpg" alt="IMG_1737.jpg" title="IMG_1737.jpg"  class="pcper-inline" width="460" height="173" /></a></div></p>
<p>Maybe best of all, this tablet starts at just $399 and is available today.</p>
<p><strong>Dell Venue 8 7000 Specifications</strong></p>
<p>Let&rsquo;s begin the review by looking at the raw specifications of the Dell Venue 8 7000. Even though hardware specifications don&rsquo;t tell a complete story of any device, especially a tablet that is based so much on experience, it is important to get a good baseline expectation.</p>
<p class="rtecenter">
<!-- Row Highlight Javascript --><!-- Row Highlight Javascript --><!-- Row Highlight Javascript --><!-- Row Highlight Javascript --><script type="text/javascript">
	window.onload=function(){

var tfrow = document.getElementById('tfhover').rows.length;
